ultural left in a broader context, challenges the dominant literary-historical narrative of the pioneer settler, and contributes to new scholarship on Canada’s modern period. By bridging close textual readings with book and publishing history, economic and sociological analysis, and original archival research, Writing Unemployment offers new ideas on work by many of Canada’s most important writers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCanadian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiberalism in literature. 0aLiberalismzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aUnemployment in literature. 0aUnemploymentxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aUnemploymentzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking class in literature. 0aWorking classzCanadaxSocial conditions. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269967040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442699670423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442699670.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK